CACOMM: Caught in an ambush firefight. He threw his body to the ground next to a guy who was firing an M16. His ear was next to the muzzle of the M16 and the gunner probably squeezed out 20 rounds while his ear was there. He thought he had been shot in the head and/or the ear but didn't see any blood. Reported to the field medic. Had short term high intensity impact noise and it was very painful for 30mins-1 hour. He was not hospitalized and did not have a gap in his memory. He thinks he was unconscious for less than 1 minute and was disoriented for 30mins-1 hour.

He is receiving benefits for an acoustic neuroma (tumor in ear) associated with loud blasts. This is most likely the TBI he is getting benefits for. He reported that he started having migraines in 1956 and in 2008 he got an MRI and they noticed the tumor. He was around a lot of aircraft noise in the 20 years he said he was in Vietnam. If passed through, he will be considered a control because his TBI does not meet threshold.
Judo injury in which a student threw him and he landed the wrong way. He got physical therapy and it doesn't cause him any pain or problems anymore.
Had major bone fusion back surgery 4 years ago but does not think he has any metal from the procedure.

TBI reported is not likely a TBI: A machine gun bounced up and hit him in the face. It burned his arms and face. He also fell through 100ft of trees after his helicopter was shot down. This seems to all have happened in the same incident.
Hit on the side of the head with a baseball bat. Did get stitches but was well enough to walk home.
Passed out while driving drunk and hit a tree. Was able to get to the side of the road and someone drove him to the hospital on base.

This WAS a penetrating injury. Involved in a spontaneous fire fight in close quarters among 6 or 8 people and his gun jammed. His recollection is that people quickly ran out of ammo so one of the others threw a rock which hit him in the head and knocked him out.  and his recollection is that people quickly ran out of ammo and one of the other people hit him with a rock and it knocked him out. The rock is what penetrated his skull down to the outer membrane but did not touch his brain. Had to be medi-vac out to the hospital so there was a lot of disorientation and confusion happening after that.

A piece of shrapnel severed a couple of nerve endings in his spine during an attack. He said it felt like a bee sting but it did result in some serious hearing loss. He has suffered hearing loss from a lot of different sources and that was one of the main ones.
Participant is having heart surgery on 12.18.12 - installing a pig valve. Contact in 6-9 months if we are still looking for eligibles.

Sitting on an open hatch, hit a mine and the hatch door flipped up and hit him in the back of the head, he was pushed down into the APC (Armored Personnel Carrier). Lost consciousness for an unknown amount of time, was enough time for people to get to the vehicle because he only woke up when people outside the APC were calling for them. Has no idea how long it took people to get to them. He went to the ER to be treated, where they were pulling all sorts of things out of him, including shrapnel, but he was not admitted to the hospital and was able to leave after being heavily bandaged.
Participant was found on the side of the road, he didn't know what was happening. They thought he was drunk but it turned out be extremely high blood pressure.

He was a jet engine mechanic. He was thrown down into a structure that keeps airplanes. It was blown up and he was thrown in the air about 2 1/2 stories. He was at the back of the aircraft that was blown up and landed on his knees and elbows. He saw dents in the metal from where he landed. He still remembers the sound of the shrapnel hitting the outside of the structure. He said the heat from the explosion helped cushion the fall (claims the heat slows down the fall) and probably kept him alive. After he fell he lost his hearing for at least a couple of days. he said it felt like he had water in his ears that he couldn't get out. After a couple of days his hearing came back. He was not hospitalized for this injury and claims he did not lose consciousness. He says he does not have a gap in his memory and he doesn't know if he was foggy/confused after the incident.

Participant is "in the middle" group and may be contacted in the future. Participant is in the middle for the following reasons: unclear service related TBI, use of exclusionary medications (opiates, benzodiazepine) and has a TICS of 26. Revisit case if needed.

This WAS a penetrating injury. Blown up on june 9th, 1969. Had shrapnel in lower left and upper left part of face, still have a few pieces in your lower body. Saw helicopter coming to get him, saw white (assumes they were nurses and doctors) and must have bled out because he can[|226|][|128|][|153|]t remember after that, the first thing he remembers is waking up in a bag. He was shipped from one hospital to another in another country and then again to another hospital in another country so for a large chunk of time after that accident, he really did not know what was going on or what was happening to him.

This WAS a penetrating injury. After much probing, indicated that he lost conscciousness for > 24 hours but this was he best guess. Used to jump out of trees onto rubber tires to make the rim go into the air and on one occasion, the rim came down onto his head and split his head open.
Car accident in which he went through the windshield about 25 or 30 feet and landed on back and head.
Fell off a rock fireplace and was hit in jaw by a steel rod.

Hydroplaned on the water and flipped over, blacked out from being underwater. The first thing he remembers is his neighbor pulling him out of the water. He remembers flipping over and then being on the boat.

This WAS a penetrating injury (had cut glass in head). car accident, hit a tree, car hanging off side of cliff, head hit on windshield. Had trauma as well because he got out just in time before the car went over the cliff. Had glass on top of head and his friend who was a medic and was with him in Vietnam pulled it out. He did not get hospitalized for it because after serving, him and this friend only trusted each other, they didn[|226|][|128|][|153|]t want to go to hospitals or see doctors.

This WAS a penetrating injury. Motorcycle accident. Was driving down 101 with about 100 friends and were pretty much the only ones on the road until a car came in the fast lane and hit them. He went flying down the road 70 mi/hr on his head, arm back, knees. He pretty much tore his right hand off but doctors were able to fix it. He also had to wear a neck brace afterwards for awhile and there was also some glass in his head from the accident. He was wearing a helmet though so that helped him to some degree. He had a flashback after this accident, it took him right back to Vietnam. When he was in the ambulance, he was right back in the helicopter in Vietnam. The accident is what spurred him to start therapy. Doesn[|226|][|128|][|153|]t remember the time shortly after being put in the ambulance and waking up in the operating room of the trauma unit.
Participant took a bunch of pills and drank wine. He was trying to commit suicide. He woke up in the hospital ward after losing consciousness for a few hours.
Participant fell when he was drunk. He hit his head, split his nose, and bruised his eye orbit (black eye). He was dizzy for a 3-4 days afterwards and thought he had vertigo.
Participant was excluded because he has MS.

While serving in Vietnam, got hit by shrapnel in the head. Shrapnel no longer there.
Was a semi-pro hockey player. Was not wearing a helmet and got checked really hard. Had to go to the hospital, but went back and played the next day.
Midair collision while flying in Vietnam. Had 2 compressed vertebraes but it did not require surgery and did not cause him any problems.
Participant was a POW - had his nose replaced due to torture in POW camp. Spent four and half years in the hospital after being rescued from POW camp to treat injuries sustained during time as POW.

Participant was blown physically into the air when a rocket propel grenade rpg exploded next to him. He was conscious after but couldn't answer questions about where/who he was. Hit neck on side of tank hatch during explosion. He went to the the army hospital for a month in Japan and then returned to Vietnam. He doesn't remember anything for several hours after the injury and he was foggy/confused for 2 days.
Participant has been sober for 9 years but used to be a terrible alcoholic after coming back from Vietnam.
Explosion - was shot in the air and landed but didn't go to the hospital. Had problems w/ hearing and vision for about 3 days. He doesn't remember the seconds between the explosion and getting up.
Working with horses in Wyoming and was hit on left side of head on metal but only cut the skin.
Participant endorsed that he had NOT had vision but had one experience when he saw himself talking to someone.
TBI reported is not a TBI - Her jeep hit a mine and turned over. No hospitalization or LOC.
Blast explosion - this is how he lost hearing. He fell asleep after the explosion when he shouldn't have. LOC for less than 5 minutes, no hospitalization.
Participant was in a car wreck and had to have stitches on his head.
Hit over the head with a lunchbox in third grade. Went to ER and had to get some stitches but no dizziness, LOC, or amnesia.
Hit in the head with part of a vent. Got stitches but no LOC, amnesia, or dizziness/disorientation.
Although the participant has never been in rehab, he does attend Alcoholics Anonymous regularly.
At pond, throwing rocks at frogs, friend throws rock, hit in the back of the head. Went home, parents took him to the hospital. No LOC, no Amnesia, no fogginess.
Was in inpatient rehab for alcohol abuse twice. Drank heavily from about 1957 to 1985 but has been sober since then.

Extra notes: Participant enlisted in US Army and transitioned to officer via OCS. Was special forces, airborne. Did 2 tours in Vietnam. Felt guilty about comrades deaths as platoon leader. Dealt with severe PTSD when he returned home. Wrote a book about his experiences.
River boat - hit sand bar - knocked out - hospitalized for 10 days
Boxing as a kid

On hill - man above hit device - got hit in left side of body - took shrapnel out.
Laying on ground, hit by grenade - no shrapnel but lost consciousness.

He was a group engineer in Jacksonville, FL. H was running a fire drill and a small boat launched off the side of the boat he was running the fire drill on. The launching boom was accidentally left on the boat and he got hit by the overhanging boom. 10 years later he got neck surgery for 2 collapsed discs and one broken disc. He has 3 fused vertebrae in his beck. LOC for only a few seconds, no hospitalization, not dazed, no amnesia. Maybe not a TBI.
Participant has had one major flashback from Vietnam in 1981. It lasted for 20 minutes and he said he was completely back in Vietnam - with sounds, smells, radio sounds, helicopters, etc...

Participant was an engineer in the coast guard and had to fabricate parts (particularly by grinding them) at times. He once got a piece of metal in his eye which has since been removed. He has not worked with metal in the last 10-12 years.
Took two rounds into his helmet but nothing penetrated. He saw stars for a few seconds but nothing else. Did result in a Class 5 headache and neck stiffness.
Nearby when an explosion occurred was knocked down but not knocked out. This was the event that caused most of his hearing loss.
Near a bomb explosion.
Near an artillery shell.

Rear-ended in the car, no hospitalization or LOC, no gap in memory or confusion. Was mainly a neck injury.

Participant suffers from hearing loss and tinnitus due to a loud explosion during Vietnam. Non TBI.

MRI - has had several. Claims he used to have some shrapnel in his body that has been removed. He also stated that he had pacing wires put in, but they were taken out at the same visit. He claims he has no metal in his body.

Has had terrible nightmares since Vietnam and would always wake up with a stiff neck and soreness. Getting into a car when the driver put the car in neutral and subject was hit in the neck by the car door. Was immediately taken to the infirmary as it happened on base and was given stitches. No LOC, no gap in memory, and slight fogginess for less than 3 minutes.

Subject reported no head or neck injuries while serving in Vietnam. However, subject did mention that there were 3 incidents in which he was nearby when a blast occurred. Drank heavily while in service and from the time he was released until 1983 when he stopped drinking. Did not drink much from 1983-2006 and then began drinking heavily again from 2006 to 2008. He started bending the rules for individuals who were falling through the cracks and could not receive help elsewhere and was eventually caught and convicted for misusing funds. He believes that his alcohol consumption contributed to him making this decision.

Car accident, hit the wall of their house. Lost all of his teeth from hitting the steering wheel. Was only hospitalized for a few hours.

Hit and run while on his bike. Hospitalized for a week in the surgical ward of the hospital he worked at. On 12/2/2013, subject was having shortness of breath that was not relieved by his prescribed inhalers. After 2 days w/o a resolution of the problem, he was admitted to the hospital. He was started on Albuterol and Atrovent inhalers and IV Solu-Medrol. His Prednisone was increased and he was placed on a weaning dose. He was discharged after 2 days. Because of a WBC level of 12.1 and bacteria in the UA on screening, the subject was asked to return to the clinic for a repeat CBC and UA. The subject returned to the clinic on 12/9/2013 for a repeat UA and CBC. He reported his recent hospitalization at that time. During the exam, he was tachypneic at rest with pursed lip breathing. Breath sounds were distant and notable for marked rales and wheezes. He was pale. The results of the WBC level were higher at 13.5; the UA was clear. Despite a history of COPD, the subject continues to smoke. When medical records were received on 12/12/2013, it was noted the subject was also in the hospital from 11/2/2013 - 11/4/2013 for cellulitis from a cat bite and exacerbation of COPD. Given the instability of the subject's COPD, he meets exclusion criteria 13 and does not meet inclusion criteria 14. The subject will not be enrolled in the study.
